02:05:37.760 --> 02:05:43.680
but they wanted to make it clear that they weren't anything to do with the Soviet Union

02:05:43.680 --> 02:05:49.920
or anything to do with Marxism. So they put the word national. Nazi is the first four letters

02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:56.560
of national, national in German, and they ZI's how you spell national in the German

02:05:56.560 --> 02:06:01.520
national socialism, but definitely not communists. That's right. They killed communists. They fought

02:06:01.520 --> 02:06:08.960
communists in the street. They had pitched battles. They literally threatened each other's existence

02:06:08.960 --> 02:06:15.040
and their life. And the first people that he arrested and put in jail were not Jews and Gypsies

02:06:15.040 --> 02:06:20.080
and all the other people he eventually killed. It was communists. They were the number one

02:06:20.080 --> 02:06:26.640
and socialist right behind them. Why? Because up until he takes power, January of 1933,

02:06:26.640 --> 02:06:33.840
that's when Hitler takes power. The last elections, two of them in 1932, the socialist and communist

02:06:33.840 --> 02:06:41.760
to vote together, 50% of the vote in Germany. So he appealed to the German manufacturers,

02:06:41.760 --> 02:06:46.480
the German capitalists, and he said, the communists and socialists are going to win.

02:06:48.400 --> 02:06:53.920
And you're just the capitalists. You have too few people. You need a mass space,

02:06:53.920 --> 02:06:56.160
and I'm the only one that can do that.

02:06:57.120 --> 02:06:59.600
So it was just the populist message that he used.

02:06:59.600 --> 02:07:07.360
That's right. But it was explicitly done as a deal. The ruling group said to Hindenburg,

02:07:07.360 --> 02:07:12.000
the old Prussian man who was in charge of the German government at the time,

02:07:12.000 --> 02:07:16.880
you have to invite Hitler to form a new government. Otherwise, he would never have done it. He had

02:07:16.880 --> 02:07:23.680
called Hitler nasty names before. The Prussian aristocracy looked down on Hitler as a little

02:07:23.680 --> 02:07:29.760
funny man with a mustache who was Austrian, wasn't even German, for them that mattered.

02:07:29.760 --> 02:07:38.480
So he comes in as the enemy, the smasher of socialism and communism, which he immediately does.

02:07:40.640 --> 02:07:46.800
Only people who don't know or care about the history pick up on the word.

02:07:47.840 --> 02:07:52.240
You know, it's like there are people here in the United States who like to say,

02:07:52.560 --> 02:08:00.880
we are not a democracy. We are a republic, which is like saying, I'm not a banana. I'm a fruit.

02:08:01.520 --> 02:08:07.840
You have to explain to these people a banana. So you have to explain to people, yes,

02:08:07.840 --> 02:08:14.080
we're a republic, but we have a commitment to democracy as a way to govern the republic,

02:08:14.080 --> 02:08:18.560
because to say you're a republic doesn't imply what kind of government you have to go through

02:08:18.560 --> 02:08:24.000
that with people, so they kind of get it. And certain words have power beyond their actual

02:08:24.000 --> 02:08:31.440
meaning that's used in communication, whether it's negative, like racist or positive, like freedom

02:08:31.440 --> 02:08:36.720
of speech or Democrat or Democrat with a D. Yeah. And then you use that to mean something.

02:08:36.720 --> 02:08:43.760
Who knows? Or negative, what, stop Donnie, stop being a socialist or something, whatever that

02:08:43.760 --> 02:08:48.240
means that's not even used as any kind of philosophical or economic sense.

02:08:48.400 --> 02:08:52.080
So let's fast forward to today. You mentioned Bernie Sanders.

02:08:53.280 --> 02:08:59.040
There's another popular figure that represents some ideas of maybe let's call it democratic

02:08:59.040 --> 02:09:04.080
socialism and maybe let's try to start to sneak up on a definition of what that could possibly

02:09:04.080 --> 02:09:14.400
mean, but AOC, Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, she's from these parts. So maybe if you can comment on

02:09:14.400 --> 02:09:23.680
Bernie Sanders or AOC, are they open to some ideas in Marxism? Are they representing those

02:09:23.680 --> 02:09:34.400
ideas well in both economic and the political sense? Okay. Where do I begin? The socialist

02:09:34.400 --> 02:09:42.800
movement predates Marx was always larger than Marx and has gone on to develop separately after

02:09:42.800 --> 02:09:50.320
Marx's death. So can we pause on that actually? Is there a nice way to delineate, draw a line

02:09:50.320 --> 02:09:58.880
between Marxism and socialism? Or if Marxism is kind of a part of socialism, can you speak to

02:09:59.840 --> 02:10:05.040
maybe try to define once again what Marxism is and what socialism is?

02:10:05.040 --> 02:10:16.560
Right. Marxism is a systematic analysis heavily focused on economics and as I said earlier,

02:10:17.280 --> 02:10:29.120
devoted to mostly a critique of capitalism and that's its strength, how it does that,

02:10:29.120 --> 02:10:36.720
how it poses the questions, how it analyzes the way capitalism works, that is really the

02:10:36.720 --> 02:10:44.880
forte of the Marxist tradition. Socialism is a bigger, broader tent within which Marxism

02:10:45.760 --> 02:10:51.360
figures it's there so that people who aren't Marxist are nonetheless aware of Marxism,

02:10:52.320 --> 02:10:59.600
like it more or less, study it more or less, but it's a broader notion that I like to use

02:10:59.600 --> 02:11:07.600
this sentence to describe. It's a broad idea that we can do better than capitalism, that really

02:11:08.160 --> 02:11:17.120
there are all kinds of things about capitalism that are not what we as modern citizens of the world

02:11:17.920 --> 02:11:24.080
think are adequate. We are in a tradition that goes back to all the people who thought they

02:11:24.080 --> 02:11:28.560
could do better than slavery and all the people who thought they could do better than feudalism.

02:11:29.760 --> 02:11:36.160
We've made progress. Fuedalism was a progress over slavery. Capitalism was a progress over both of

02:11:36.160 --> 02:11:45.360
them and progress hasn't stopped and we are the people who in a variety of ways want the progress

02:11:46.000 --> 02:11:54.640
to go further and are not held back by believing that capitalism is somehow the best beyond which

02:11:54.640 --> 02:12:02.320
we cannot go or even think. We find that to be, in the worst sense of the word, a reactionary way

02:12:02.320 --> 02:12:09.200
of thinking and we're that large community. Many of us are not interested in economics all that

02:12:09.200 --> 02:12:17.840
much. We don't think that's the focal area. We are socialists, for example, because we want to do

02:12:17.840 --> 02:12:25.920
something to deal with climate change. We think the world is about to kill itself physically

02:12:25.920 --> 02:12:33.840
and we want to take steps with other people to stop that, to fix that, etc. So that's for me

02:12:34.720 --> 02:12:42.160
a kind of difference. It's a little difficult to say because there's no other figure like Marx

02:12:42.960 --> 02:12:50.080
that has an equal impact, an equal place within the broad socialist tradition.

02:12:50.720 --> 02:12:59.840
The only tradition that comes close might be the anarchist tradition, but that's very specialized

02:12:59.920 --> 02:13:06.240
and that's a whole other kind of conversation. Whatever you say, the influence of the great

02:13:06.240 --> 02:13:16.080
anarchist thinkers, Kropotkin, Bakunin, Sorrell, and others still doesn't amount to the impact that

02:13:16.080 --> 02:13:27.360
Marx and Marxism have had so far. That could change, but up to this point that's a way of

02:13:27.360 --> 02:13:31.600
understanding the relationship. Yeah, that's interesting that some of the ideas within

02:13:32.240 --> 02:13:38.880
anarchism, and of course it's one of the more varied disciplines, because there's such,

02:13:39.760 --> 02:13:45.280
maybe by definition, such variety in their thinkers, but they kind of stand for a

02:13:48.080 --> 02:13:55.840
dismantling of a power center and that, if not equates, tends to rhyme with some of the ideas

02:13:55.840 --> 02:14:02.880
of socialism. Absolutely. So where you have the... There's a whole train of thought in socialist ideas

02:14:02.880 --> 02:14:11.760
and in Marxist ideas that uses the phrase, quote, the withering away of the state. That's a quotation

02:14:11.760 --> 02:14:21.120
from Lenin. People should understand that's a quotation from Lenin and it was made by Lenin,

02:14:21.120 --> 02:14:26.480
positive. In other words, Lenin was saying, that's a good thing. That's something we stand for.

02:14:27.040 --> 02:14:32.400
We want to create the conditions under which there is a... Because you remember, the

02:14:33.040 --> 02:14:38.400
communists or whatever, they wouldn't call that at first in Russia before the revolution. They

02:14:38.400 --> 02:14:43.680
were just socialists. They were hunted down and persecuted by the government left and right.

02:14:43.680 --> 02:14:49.280
They had no love for the government. The government was their literal everyday enemy and

02:14:49.520 --> 02:14:56.160
being critical of government didn't just mean this particular government, but of the whole...

02:14:56.800 --> 02:15:02.400
Being a Marxist, you always ask the questions of the social constitution of whatever it is

02:15:02.400 --> 02:15:08.480
you're struggling against. So there was this interest, why is the state so important? Especially

02:15:08.480 --> 02:15:14.560
because if you understand feudalism, particularly early feudalism, it didn't have powerful states.

02:15:15.200 --> 02:15:21.920
One of Lenin's greatest books is called The Economic History of Russia and he goes back centuries.

02:15:21.920 --> 02:15:26.880
It's a huge book, three or four inches thick and I'm one of the few people who've read it.

02:15:30.240 --> 02:15:36.000
He's very good about the absence of a strong central government in many parts of feudalism,

02:15:36.000 --> 02:15:41.920
including inside Russia, but also in other parts of Europe. The development of a powerful central

02:15:41.920 --> 02:15:49.440
state comes towards the end of feudalism as it is desperate to hold on, which ought to be suggestive

02:15:49.440 --> 02:15:57.360
that maybe the turn to powerful governments here in the United States or in Europe is maybe also

02:15:57.360 --> 02:16:06.240
because this system is exhausted and can't go on and has to marshal every last bit of power it can

02:16:07.040 --> 02:16:13.040
not to be lost in history. It would be interesting to see what the Soviet Union

02:16:13.040 --> 02:16:18.960
would look like if Lenin never died. A lot of people have asked that question over the years,

02:16:18.960 --> 02:16:24.160
a lot of people. The area is stalling, sliding in in the middle of the night,

02:16:24.160 --> 02:16:30.240
erasing the withering away of the state part. Yes, exactly. So just to return briefly back

02:16:30.240 --> 02:16:35.440
to AOC and Bernie Sanders, what are your thoughts about these modern political figures that represent

02:16:35.440 --> 02:16:39.920
some of these ideas and they sometimes refer to those ideas as democratic socialism? Right.

